    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-17T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-17T18:00:00-05:00" n="1180"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1180">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 125.0067/17</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgenthau</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-17T18:00:00-05:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">November 17, 1914, 6 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>37. Your 21, November 12, 3 p.m., received to-day. You may strongly protest
                    against the Turkish authorities searching all consulates in charge of American
                    representatives and everything therein <pb facs="1062" n="748" xml:id="pg_748"/>
                    except archives. You may, if not too late, instruct American consular
                    representatives to be present unofficially in order that they may later give
                    testimony as to the acts of the Turkish authorities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
